<FONT CLASS="title16">About the Rind</FONT><BR>  
<font class="bodyCopySmall">    
	   
You'll note that when we grate your cheese to order, we give you any 
leftover pieces of rind. We think it's an honest way of doing business. 
And you can toss that piece of rind into soups and stews as a flavoring 
(but don't serve it to your guests, it's a bit chewy).
<P>
And while on the subject of rinds, we'll shed some light on that ancient 
query, "Can I eat the rind?" Rinds will rarely kill you, but they may 
not always be very tasty. We offer the following guidelines:
<P>
<b>Moldy Rinds on Goat Cheese</b><BR>
The moldy rind on an aged ch&egrave;vre is considered important to the cheese's 
flavor, but there is no shame in trimming it off.
<P>
<b>Brie and Camembert Rinds</b><BR>
Bries and Camemberts are cased in an edible, velvety white mold rind. 
Some great connoisseurs insist you <i>must</i> eat the rind &#151; it's 
the best part. Other equally great connoisseurs demand that you trim off 
the rind, lest its moldy flavor detract from the cheese's delicate 
complexity. The choice is yours.
<P>
<b>Washed-Rind Cheeses</b><BR>
Washed-rind cheeses, such as St. Nectaire, Pavin, and Chaumes, have 
crusty, orange-colored rinds that are generally considered edible, 
though a little bitter-tasting and occasionally gritty.
<P>
<b>Natural Rinds of Hard Cheeses</b><BR>
The rinds of hard aged cheeses are not usually edible, though they 
probably won't hurt you. Parmesan and Grana rinds are great for flavoring 
soups and stews.
<P>
<b>Cheeses Bound in Wax, Foil, or Cloth</b><BR>
Don't eat wax, foil, or cloth.<BR>

